Having been to Gary Danko multiple times now during different times of the year, I've had the opportunity to try a vast array of their menu as it changes throughout the seasons. Gary Danko is the perfect place for a date night or for a special celebration. Sure, it's on the pricier side but it's such an amazing deal for the quality and quantity that you get. The way it works is that you first choose how many courses you'd like, anywhere from 3-5. And then, the menu is all for the choosing. If you want 5 entrees, you can get 5 entrees! Or maybe you want 2 desserts? You got it. I like the flexibility they offer as it allows me to try everything and anything I want. The menu here stays pretty consistent in terms of the proteins they offer. They'll change the sauces depending on what's in season and the way it's cooked, but otherwise they always have the same selection of seafood and meats. I usually go for all seafood as it's not as heavy and I am able to order the 5-course and finish it completely :) My top favs for apps/entrees: Seared Sea Scallops Seared Ahi Tuna Glazed Oysters Roast Maine Lobster For desserts, I highly recommend any of their souffles as they are made to perfection. You really cannot go wrong ever! Also, for any first timers-- they'll always give you a rectangular plate with extra mini-pastries/desserts. If you're too full, just bring it home! And then at the end of your meal, they'll give you a little breakfast cake. The flavor depends on the season but in the past, I've had pineapple and pumpkin.

Would of been 5 stars but the waitress Susanne rushed my group out of the private room after we paid. She had another party/reservation for the private room after ours and was rude in the way she requested us to leave. Needing time to prepare for another group is understandable but there are polite ways of explaining this. The food was good. Good experience up until the end. All that good food just to leave a bad taste in your mouth.

The menu are extensive, we both decided to do one appetizer and two main dish. The appetizer, I ordered the risotto and my boyfriend ordered the crab cake. The risotto are very creamy and the amount for appetizer are just perfectly right. The crab cake is one of the highlight for tonight. They gave real crab meat in it, and the overall display of the dish are well done. Main dish, I had the lemon pepper duck breast, and my boyfriend had the lamb. The duck breast is medium rare, the sauce is wonderful and the dish is one of my favorite for tonight. The lamb is alright, nothing too special. Another main dish we ordered are the Maine lobster and beef. Beef is the most disappointing dish, is very dried and although it is suppose to be medium rare. It is over cook... First review of 2020 goes to one of my all-time favorite restaurants - Gary Danko! I've been here 3 times, with the most recent visit being on Christmas Eve with my whole family of 9. We got seated in the back private dining room. What I love most about their tasting menu is that you can choose 3, 4, or 5 courses, and you can pick from any category. For example, if you want 5 meat courses, go for it! I decided to go with 2 appetizers (oysters w/ caviar; risotto), 1 seafood (lobster), 1 meat (duck breast), and 1 dessert (espresso gateau). My boyfriend, on the other hand, also got the risotto, but for his next 4 courses, he ordered the coconut Thai seafood curry, venison, stuffed quail, and a cheesecake. The menu is quite extensive, and the portions are pretty substantial. Honestly, I would've been content at 3 courses, but the price difference to add 2 more courses was about ~$50, so why not? I would say, however, since my first time dining here more than 10 years ago, the menu hasn't changed much. Creativity-wise, they play it safe, but execution-wise, they are phenomenal and right-on-point. Service was great as well. This time, we also ordered wine pairings. I guess every restaurant does this differently. Here, they offered me 2 whites and 2 reds for $80, while they poured 1 white and 1 red for the bf for $40 since he was driving, which worked out perfectly. Again, the ability to customize your meal here is what sets it apart from other Michelin-star restaurants.

I not bore you with a detailed review. Simply the best, it is expensive, it is worth it. No doubt. Enjoy !

I can safely say that Gary Danko has flawless execution of service and delicious variety of dishes with high quality ingredients. This has been far one of my favorite meals in SF, Michelin or not. The full menu is divided into five sections: appetizers, seafood, meats, cheese, and desserts. You have the option of choosing 3, 4, or 5 courses ($97, $120, $143 respectively). They also let you know that you can double up on anything or choice any combination of dishes! Appetizers: Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing - very flavorful and citrus-y Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Celery Root and White Beech Mushrooms - rich with flavor, generous on the seafood Seafood: Coconut Thai Curry with Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Candied Peanuts and Shiitake Mushrooms - very generous on the seafood (and portion overall), great flavors, careful presentation/pour at the table Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Edamame, Blood Orange and Basil - smaller portion, nice quality, really liked the flavor on blood orange Meats: Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Bordelaise Butter and Cassis-Shallot Marmalade - generous portion, perfect sear Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Celeriac-Garlic Purée, Belgian Endive and Cardamom Poached Pears - very interesting combination of flavors and texture, duck was very good Desserts: Seasonal Sorbet or Ice Cream Sampler with Cookies - the flavors right now are a citrus, passionfruit, and tumeric something (I don't remember!) Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces - beautiful texture in chocolate heaven The endless bread is addictive! Careful not to fill up too much :P This entire meal was carefully serviced and executed. I'd highly recommend this for a special occasion (although at this price range, I wouldn't mind coming back somewhat frequently heh). The crowd definitely skews more on the older end, which I think goes to show the longevity of the restaurant and its longstanding reputation.

I won't lie, Gary Danko gave off a very pretentious vibe that made my partner and I feel slightly uncomfortable the entire night. To top it all off, we only felt that a few of the dishes were extraordinary, and the majority of the dishes were just OK. Service staff was very professional in clearing dishes and filling drinks. But the sommelier and the main waitress for our table seemed condescending, perhaps because my partner and I are young. It shouldn't matter though; we are paying customers regardless of age. Especially in a city like San Francisco, the attitude was unexpected. Best thing of our 8 dishes were the oysters -- superb. Best cooked oysters either of us had ever tried. Risotto, salmon, and duck were ok, nothing extraordinary. Branzini was also lacking the ummff that we were looking for. Texture was great, flavor was meh. Nothing except the oysters stands out. Gary Danko's not a very experimental place. We were celebrating a birthday and an anniversary, and Gary Danko did bring out complimentary desserts for the occasion. They were tasty and definitely appreciated. I am honestly confused about all the great reviews. Might be that after spending so much $$$$, you're looking for reasons why the money was worth it. They do nothing wrong necessarily (except the attitude could be more welcoming), and the food isn't offensive at all - just not very impressive. It's still a nice night out, but I won't be looking for reasons to return.

    Having been to Gary Danko multiple times now during different times of the year, I've had the opportunity to try a vast array of their menu as it changes throughout the seasons. Gary Danko is the perfect place for a date night or for a special celebration. Sure, it's on the pricier side but it's such an amazing deal for the quality and quantity that you get.

    The way it works is that you first choose how many courses you'd like, anywhere from 3-5. And then, the menu is all for the choosing. If you want 5 entrees, you can get 5 entrees! Or maybe you want 2 desserts? You got it. I like the flexibility they offer as it allows me to try everything and anything I want.

    The menu here stays pretty consistent in terms of the proteins they offer. They'll change the sauces depending on what's in season and the way it's cooked, but otherwise they always have the same selection of seafood and meats.

    I usually go for all seafood as it's not as heavy and I am able to order the 5-course and finish it completely :)

    My top favs for apps/entrees:
    Seared Sea Scallops
    Seared Ahi Tuna
    Glazed Oysters
    Roast Maine Lobster

    For desserts, I highly recommend any of their souffles as they are made to perfection. You really cannot go wrong ever!

    Also, for any first timers-- they'll always give you a rectangular plate with extra mini-pastries/desserts. If you're too full, just bring it home! And then at the end of your meal, they'll give you a little breakfast cake. The flavor depends on the season but in the past, I've had pineapple and pumpkin.

    I can safely say that Gary Danko has flawless execution of service and delicious variety of dishes with high quality ingredients. This has been far one of my favorite meals in SF, Michelin or not.

    The full menu is divided into five sections: appetizers, seafood, meats, cheese, and desserts. You have the option of choosing 3, 4, or 5 courses  ($97, $120, $143 respectively). They also let you know that you can double up on anything or choice any combination of dishes!

    Appetizers:
    Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing - very flavorful and citrus-y
    Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Celery Root and White Beech Mushrooms - rich with flavor, generous on the seafood

    Seafood:
    Coconut Thai Curry with Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Candied Peanuts and Shiitake Mushrooms - very generous on the seafood (and portion overall), great flavors, careful presentation/pour at the table
    Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Edamame, Blood Orange and Basil - smaller portion, nice quality, really liked the flavor on blood orange

    Meats:
    Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Bordelaise Butter and Cassis-Shallot Marmalade - generous portion, perfect sear
    Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Celeriac-Garlic Purée, Belgian Endive and Cardamom Poached Pears - very interesting combination of flavors and texture, duck was very good

    Desserts:
    Seasonal Sorbet or Ice Cream Sampler with Cookies - the flavors right now are a citrus, passionfruit, and tumeric something (I don't remember!)
    Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces - beautiful texture in chocolate heaven

    The endless bread is addictive! Careful not to fill up too much :P This entire meal was carefully serviced and executed. I'd highly recommend this for a special occasion (although at this price range, I wouldn't mind coming back somewhat frequently heh). The crowd definitely skews more on the older end, which I think goes to show the longevity of the restaurant and its longstanding reputation.

    -you can do the prefixed tasting or make your own for the same price, mixing and matching any items you want (including the prefix ones... or you could do five desserts).

    The service... Andrew was our primary server and he was fantastic. Attentive, entertaining, very sociable and interactive answering even my very basic questions.

    The atmosphere was fantastic! Everyone there was so happy with their food and service, it created a comfortable noise level of pleased people.

    They are excellent with taking photos for you. Don't feel bad when they use the flash, it makes the pic better and again everyone's celebrating.

    Cocktails and wine pairing: we both planned to do the pairing but the first cocktail was Exceptional so I did the wine pairing and bae did the cocktails- for someone who makes cocktails it was very fun to discuss the spirits and what made their cocktails so delicious. The wine pairings were perfect and the wine tasted Amazing!

    The food was Delicious!
    -a bite of onion soup (the best I've ever had)
    -caviar buckwheat salmon (one of the more memorable foods I've ever eaten).
    -lobster (delicious sauce- one of the best we've had)
    -oysters (one of the best soups of my life)
    -flambeed bananas (better than bananas foster in NOLA)
    -bison (the most tender and least gamey I've ever had)
    -seared ahi tuna (can I eat this every day? It was perfect)

    The oysters, duck, and beef were good, but for eating at a fancy restaurant they werent as wowing for us. All of the desserts were good as well.

    We're already planning an excuse for our next visit!

    I won't lie, Gary Danko gave off a very pretentious vibe that made my partner and I feel slightly uncomfortable the entire night. To top it all off, we only felt that a few of the dishes were extraordinary, and the majority of the dishes were just OK. Definitely not the level of food or service we expected given the price point.

    Hostesses were very friendly and getting all of the reservations sorted out. Service staff was very professional in clearing dishes and filling drinks. But the sommelier and the main waitress for our table seemed condescending, perhaps because my partner and I are young. It shouldn't matter though; we are paying customers regardless of age. Especially in a city like San Francisco, the attitude was unexpected.

    Best thing of our 8 dishes were the oysters -- superb. Best cooked oysters either of us had ever tried. Risotto, salmon, and duck were ok, nothing extraordinary. Branzini was also lacking the ummff that we were looking for. Texture was great, flavor was meh. Nothing except
    the oysters stands out. Gary Danko's not a very experimental place.

    We were celebrating a birthday and an anniversary, and Gary Danko did bring out complimentary desserts for the occasion. They were tasty and definitely appreciated.

    I am honestly confused about all the great reviews. Might be that after spending so much $$$$, you're looking for reasons why the money was worth it. They do nothing wrong necessarily (except the attitude could be more welcoming), and the food isn't offensive at all - just not very impressive. It's still a nice night out, but I won't be looking for reasons to return.

    This was a celebratory outing for my parents' 30th anniversary, and Gary Danko did not disappoint. As soon as we stepped in, we got our coats/jackets taken and we got seated in a spacious booth for 4 people. We were then immediately greeted and ordered a bottle of champagne to celebrate.

    As far as the menu goes, we were told there were 4 options: chef's choice, or a mix of 3, 4, or 5 appetizers/fish/meat/dessert/cheese courses. Most of us chose 3.

    Gary Danko is one of two restaurants I have been to in my life that creates an experience that is worth the money, with Bacchanalia in Atlanta being the other.  First, this dinner shouldn't have happened.  I had called several months in advance to try and get a reservation for the week of Thanksgiving 2019.  There was nothing.  On a chance, and knowing how much I wanted to dine there, my husband called when we arrived in San Francisco and got a reservation!  I was so excited.

    Everything was superb. Typically when I do a review, I look at decor, waitstaff, presentation, food, and timelessness. Everything is what you would expect from the Michelin rated and James Beard award-winning restaurant.  What stood out as the highlight of our experience was the sommelier that educated us on the wine pairings accompanying our five-course price-fixed meal. The sommelier introduced each wine that would be complementing each course of our meal.  He was not only knowledgable on an expert level; he took the time to answer our questions, helping us truly appreciate the reasoning behind each selection.  This in turn, elevated our overall dining experience.

    Our teenaged daughter decided to stay at the hotel.  We had encouraged her to join us, but she was exhausted from our day of sightseeing.  We had made small talk with our head waiter, and at the end of our meal, we were not only treated so a delicious sampling of small sweets, but the head waiter had also prepared one to take back to our daughter!  It was a multitude of little things like this gesture, making this experience a once in a lifetime memory for me.
